Section 1: Q&A; Pairs

Example 1.1

User

What is reinforcement learning?
AI Response

Reinforcement learning trains an agent to make decisions by interacting with an environment and receiving
rewards or penalties, aiming to maximize cumulative reward over time.

Example 1.2

User

What is a convolutional neural network?
AI Response

A CNN uses convolutional layers to automatically learn spatial features from images. Pooling layers reduce
dimensionality. CNNs are the standard for image classification and detection tasks.

Example 1.3

User

What is the bias-variance tradeoff?
AI Response

High bias = underfitting (oversimplified model); high variance = overfitting (over-complex model). Good
models balance both to minimize total prediction error.

Example 1.4

User

What is tokenization in NLP?
AI Response

Tokenization splits text into smaller units (tokens) such as words, subwords, or characters. Subword
tokenization (BPE, WordPiece) balances vocabulary size with handling of rare words.

Example 1.5

User

What is fine-tuning?
AI Response

Fine-tuning updates a pre-trained model's weights on a smaller, task-specific dataset. It is more efficient than
training from scratch and achieves strong performance with limited data.

Example 1.6

User

What is a hyperparameter?
AI Response

A hyperparameter is a configuration setting external to the model—like learning rate or batch size—set
before training and tuned using validation performance.

Example 1.7

User

What is the vanishing gradient problem?
AI Response



In deep networks, gradients shrink exponentially during backpropagation, preventing early layers from
learning. Solutions include ReLU activations, residual connections, and LSTMs.

Example 1.8

User

What is data augmentation?
AI Response

Data augmentation artificially increases training data by applying transformations like rotation, cropping, and
flipping to existing samples, improving model generalization.

Example 1.9

User

What is BERT?
AI Response

BERT (Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers) is a pre-trained transformer model that
understands context from both directions in a sentence, excelling at NLP classification tasks.

Example 1.10

User

What is GPT?
AI Response

GPT (Generative Pre-trained Transformer) is an autoregressive language model trained to predict the next
token. GPT-3 and GPT-4 are large-scale versions capable of diverse language tasks.



